Are you guys sure that is same problem ?
The problem in this PR has the following characteristics:
- UI partially frozen:
    you can select the menus but can't activate them
    you can drag the Srollbar thump up and down but the editor won't scroll
- Expanding or Collapsing a TreeItem brings eclipse back to normal.
- It happens quite often

Please take a look at Bug#33652, maybe that's the problem you guys are having. 

FYI, the fix was applied in the method Canvas.scroll():
before copying area swt needs to flush all the outstanding paints, what used to 
be done like this:
//	OS.gdk_flush ();
//	while ((OS.gtk_events_pending()) != 0) {
//		OS.gtk_main_iteration ();
//	}
Since this was causing the problem it was changed to: 
	OS.gdk_flush ();
	int window = paintWindow ();
	OS.gdk_window_process_updates (window, false);

Does someone can reproduce this bug using the steps in comment #28 ?

I do think that *this* bug is fixed, what you guys are having is a different 
one. Note that tracking different bugs in different problem reports is much 
better for everybody.  

Reopen this again if I wrong.

We have narrowed the problem down to this simple test case:

public static void main(String[] args) {
	Display display = new Display();
	Shell shell = new Shell(display);
	Tree tree = new Tree(shell, SWT.BORDER);
	tree.setBounds(10, 10, 100, 80);
	for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
		TreeItem item = new TreeItem(tree, SWT.NONE);
		for (int j = 0; j < 1; j++) {
			TreeItem subItem = new TreeItem(item, SWT.NONE);
		}
	}
//	tree.setBounds(10, 10, 100, 80);
	shell.setBounds(10, 10, 140, 140);
	shell.open();
	while (!shell.isDisposed()) {
		if (!display.readAndDispatch())
			display.sleep();
	}
	display.dispose();
}

If the bounds on the tree are set before the items are added, the CPU gets 
pegged.  It is necessary that the size of the tree be small enough to require 
a scrollbar.

We are going to reproduce the error in a simple C example and will submit a 
bug report to GTK.  We will update this bug report with the GTK bug number at 
that time.
